f joint capsule fibres"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe formation of synovial joints begins with \u003Cstrong\u003Econdensation of mesenchymal cells\u003C/strong\u003E between the cartilage models of developing bones. This is followed by differentiation of these cells into specific joint tissues. The process continues with cavitation of the condensed mesenchyme to form the joint space, followed by differentiation of surrounding tissues into the synovial membrane, capsule, and supporting ligaments.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options represent later events or misconceptions about joint formation:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESecretion of synovial fluid\u003C/strong\u003E only begins after the joint cavity has formed through cavitation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOssification of articular surfaces\u003C/strong\u003E is not part of synovial joint formation - the articular surfaces remain cartilaginous\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFormation of blood vessels\u003C/strong\u003E occurs later in development to supply the developing joint tissues\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDevelopment of joint capsule fibres\u003C/strong\u003E occurs after the initial mesenchymal condensation phase\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Synovial joint formation occurs through cavitation of mesenchymal tissue between developing bones.","During synovial joint formation the articular cartilage develops from the mesenchymal tissue at the ends of developing bones.","During synovial joint formation the synovial membrane develops from the inner layer of mesenchymal tissue surrounding the joint cavity."],"references":["Sadler TW. Langman\u0027s Medical Embryology: Wolters Kluwer; 2015.","Chijimatsu R, Sait